\title{Limits and colimits in Markov Categories}
\parent{efr-AK18}

\p{
  We will need to impose several different categorical properties on our Markov categories. These are analogues of preexisting properties of ordinary categories, but will typically need to be modified somewhat to suit Markov categories. The usual pattern is to demand that #{\cC_\det} has some property, and that this is "preserved" by the inclusion into #{\cC}. We list these now.
}

\p{
  The list of hypotheses we will chiefly be interested in is the following:
  \ol{
    \li{
      #{\cC_\det} is Boolean, countably complete and (countably) extensive (so that it receives a unique functor from #{\Borel} by Chen's theorem).
    }
    \li{
      The inclusion #{\cC_\det \into \cC} preserves the countable coproducts, the pullbacks along coproduct inclusions (hence all monomorphisms), and carries the countable products to Kolmogorov products.
    }
  }
}

\p{
  There are various ways we can break this up into sub-assumptions. For example, if #{\cC} admits Kolmogorov products of a given cardinality, #{\cC_\det} admits products of that cardinality. So if #{\cC} has countable Kolmogorov products and #{\cC_\det} has pullbacks along monomorphisms, #{\cC_\det} has all limits.
}

\subtree{
