  \ol{
  \li{
    In the Cartesian case, if #{\cC} is Boolean, countably complete and extensive, then it is also countably extensive (\ref{chen-universal-stdborel-2019}, Lemma 2.5). However, the proof of this relies on identifying morphisms #{X \to Y} with their graphs (subobjects of #{X \times Y}), and applying our knowledge about the subobject lattice. In the Markov context, we can not necessarily identify a morphism with a deterministic subobject of #{X}, hence this argument does not work. If the category is representable, we can of course apply the preceding lemma.
  }

