  \li{
    Let #{\cC, \cD} are Markov categories with countable Kolmogorov products, so that #{\cC_\det, \cD_\det} is countably extensive and Boolean, and the inclusons preserve this functor, and let #{F: \cC \to \cD} is a strong Markov functor. Suppose #{F_\det : \cC_\det \to \cD_\det} preserves countable limits and finite coproducts. Then it automatically preserves countable coproducts as well (again, by Chen's argument). Since these are the same as the countable coproducts in #{\cC, \cD}, it follows that #{F} preserves countable coproducts as well.
